-> Immutable :
        The term "immutable" refers to an object or data structure whose state cannot be modified after it is created.

-> Creation: 
       public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Creating string objects
        String str1 = "Hello";
        String str2 = "World";

        // Concatenating strings creates a new string
        String combined = str1 + ", " + str2;

        // Original strings remain unchanged
        System.out.println("str1: " + str1); // Output: "Hello"
        System.out.println("str2: " + str2); // Output: "World"

        // The result of concatenation is a new string
        System.out.println("combined: " + combined); // Output: "Hello, World"

        // Creating a substring also creates a new string
        String substring = combined.substring(0, 5);
        System.out.println("substring: " + substring); // Output: "Hello"
        }

        We create two string objects, str1 and str2.
        Concatenating str1 and str2 with the + operator creates a new string object combined. The original strings str1 and str2 remain unchanged.
        Creating a substring using substring method also creates a new string object substring.
